    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1968-11-23T10:40:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1968-11-23T10:40:00-05:00" n="440"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d440">
                <head>440. Action Memorandum From the Presidentʼs Special Assistant (<persName
                        corresp="#p_RWW1" type="from">Rostow</persName>) to President <persName
                        corresp="#p_JLB1" type="to">Johnson</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d440fn1">Source: Johnson Library, National
                        Security File, Country File, Guyana (Brit. G.), Vol. I, Cables, Memos, and
                        Misc., 5/66–11/68. Secret.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1968-11-23T10:40:00-05:00">November 23, 1968, 10:40 a.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Loan for Guyana Rice Industry</item>
                </list>
                <p>Bill <persName corresp="#p_GWS1">Gaud</persName> is asking urgently for your
                    approval of a $12.9 million loan to modernize the rice industry in Guyana (Tab
                        B).<note n="2" xml:id="d440fn2">Reference is to a November 18 memorandum
                        from <persName corresp="#p_GWS1">Gaud</persName> to the President, attached
                        but not printed.</note> Charlie Zwick <pb facs="1000" n="965"
                        xml:id="pg_965"/> recommends your approval (Tab A).<note n="3"
                        xml:id="d440fn3">Memorandum from Zwick to the President, November 21,
                        attached but not printed.</note> Treasury has no problem on balance of
                    payments grounds.</p>
                <p>The critical elections in Guyana will take place December 16. Prime Minister
                        <persName corresp="#p_BLFS1">Burnham</persName> has done a very good job of
                    preparing the political ground to fend off <persName corresp="#p_JCB1">Cheddi
                        Jagan</persName>ʼs challenge at the polls. Although the East Indian
                    population outnumbers <persName corresp="#p_BLFS1">Burnham</persName>ʼs
                    predominently black following, some of <persName corresp="#p_JCB1"
                        >Jagan</persName>ʼs supporters have been won over by <persName
                        corresp="#p_BLFS1">Burnham</persName>ʼs good government record. The outlook
                    is for a very narrow <persName corresp="#p_BLFS1">Burnham</persName> victory,
                    barring last-minute surprises.</p>
                <p>This rice loan project plays a key part in <persName corresp="#p_BLFS1"
                        >Burnham</persName>ʼs electoral strategy. The governmentʼs efforts to
                    modernize Guyanaʼs rice industry, well publicized for over a year, will help
                    split <persName corresp="#p_JCB1">Jagan</persName>ʼs almost solid political
                    support among the small rice farmers, all of whom are East Indian. The project
                    has been delayed for technical reasons long past the intended starting date.
                    Nonetheless, announcement of the loan within the next few days will still have
                    important political benefits for <persName corresp="#p_BLFS1">Burnham</persName>
                    and help to guarantee his election.</p>
                <p>This is a good project on its economic merits. The overriding argument, however,
                    is that it provides important political support for <persName corresp="#p_BLFS1"
                        >Burnham</persName> at this crucial point. Ambassador <persName
                        corresp="#p_CDR1">Carlson</persName> urges your approval in time for an
                    announcement to be made in Georgetown early next week.</p>
                <p>I recommended that you approve authorization of this loan.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_RWW1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Walt</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p rend="flushleft">Approve<note n="4" xml:id="d440fn4">This option is
                            checked.</note>
                    </p>
                    <p rend="flushleft">Disapprove</p>
                    <p rend="flushleft">See me</p>
                </postscript>
            </div>
